<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PUK Declares Unilateral Cease-fire in N. Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) has declared a unilateral cease-fire in northern
Iraq starting from Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The PUK called in a press release the Kurdistan Democratic
Party (KDP), a rivaling Kurdish group, to make a similar decision
to help reach a peace settlement of their disputes, the Iraqi News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the KDP to help end the Turkish interference in
the affairs of northern Iraq and preserve Iraqi sovereignty and
political independence.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that the KDP accepted the cease-fire Friday.
It said in a statement that, from now on it would "refrain from
launching a counter-attack."
</P>
<P>
The truce was reportedly mediated by the United States, Britain
and Turkey, the three sponsors of the two-year-old Ankara
process.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, Turkey bombed PUK-controlled areas in its
military operations in northern Iraq against Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK). The KDP, backed by Turkey, has been
fighting against the PKK in the area alongside with Turkish troops.
</P>
<P>
The PUK, led by Jalal Talabani, and the KDP, headed by Massoud
Barzani, have been fighting against each other for the control of
northern Iraq after President Saddam Hussein failed to exert
effective influence in the area due to a crushing defeat in the
1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Fierce fighting erupted last week between the two groups
following the failure of the talks they held in London with
observers from the United States, Britain and Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
