<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Assists Zimbabwe In Curbing Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's malaria control
program received two million Zimbabwe Dollars (160,000 U.S.
Dollars) from the World Health Organisation, Secretary of
Zimbabwe's Health and Child Welfare Ministry Paulinius Sikosana
said today.
</P>
<P>
About 600,000 cases of malaria and 3,000 deaths were reported
throughout the country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, Sikosana said incidence of malaria dropped by about
30 percent this year while mortality had fallen by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
''This was due to a combination of factors, including improved
financial and material resources, intensification of spray
programmes and community awareness programmes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He said icon, a pyrethroid insecticide which had been used to
successfully control malaria in a number of countries, had
received favourable response from local communities throughout
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
