<HEADLINE> UK Likely to Rule Out First-Wave EMU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government is on
the verge of ruling out the possibility of Britain joining the
European Monetary Union (EMU) in the first wave, according to a
report in today's Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an exclusive interview with the Times, British
Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown gave the strongest signal
so far that Britain would not join the single European currency
named euro before its official launch date on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Brown, who is commonly regarded a pro-European, said that it
was "highly unlikely" that Britain would enter in 1999 and he
would not be forced into a decision for "short-term political
reasons" and would concentrate first on achieving "sustainable
growth."
</P>
<P>
"If we do not join in 1999, our task will be to deliver a
period of sustainable growth, tackle the long term weaknesses of
the UK economy and to continue to press for reform of Europe," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Political commentators predict that the Chancellor is expected
to formally announce that Britain would not join the first wave of
the single European currency over the next few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
