<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Landmines to Be Cleared in Northeast Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
soon launch a major project to clear a potentially dangerous
minefield along the northeastern border, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project financed by the European Union and the Ministry of
Defence is already inviting international tenders to undertake
the task.
</P>
<P>
About two million anti-personnel landmines were planted in
seven minefields in the country since 1963 till to independence,
particularly on the northern border with Zambia and the eastern
and northeastern border with Mozambique. The landmines were
planted as part of the military strategy supporting continued
white minority rule in the country which ended with independence
in 1980.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC), there are an estimated 20 million mines in southern
Africa, one fifth of those in the world, representing a direct
threat to the health, welfare and survival of many millions of
people, mainly in the worst affected nations of Angola and
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Anti-personnel mines constitute a major obstacle to
post-conflict reconstruction and development in southern Africa,
hence the resolve by the Zimbabwean government to rid the country
of these weapons of destruction.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe recently signed a treaty in support of a global ban
on the production, stockpiling, transfer and use of
anti-personnel landmines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
