<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ANC Supports Mandela's Visit to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The African National
Congress (ANC) today threw its weight behind South African
President Nelson Mandela's state visit to Libya next week.
</P>
<P>
"The African National Congress fully supports President Nelson
Mandela's visit to north African countries including Egypt and
Libya," a statement of the ANC said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after criticisms of the visit from
opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
National Party spokesman Boy Geldenhuys said Friday that
Mandela should cancel his visit to Libya as it held serious
detrimental consequences for South Africa's national interests.
</P>
<P>
The visit would not only put South Africa on a collision
course with the mainstream of international politics, but could
also damage relations with the United States which regards Libya
sponsor of international terrorism and seeks to isolate it both
politically and economically.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party leader Tony Leon said at the same day that
Mandela's visit was another foreign relations embarrassment for
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The visit violates several U.N. resolutions and jeopardizes
our friendly relationship with countries like the United States
and Britain," he said.
</P>
<P>
In response, the ANC statement said: "The ANC urges President
Mandela not to entertain concerns from parties of apartheid --
the Democratic Party and the National Party -- in this regard."
</P>
<P>
"South Africa as a new democratic country should not allow its
foreign policy to be guided by apartheid perceptions of foreign
relations," it added.
</P>
<P>
"We are of the view as the ANC that South Africa should
continue to develop and cultivate relations that will lead to
understanding and cooperation among countries of the continent of
Africa."
</P>
<P>
Washington, as expected, also expressed disapproval of
Mandela's visit to Libya.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Foley said Thursday: "We
would reiterate the fact that, according to U.N. Security Council
Resolutions 748 and 883, flights into Tripoli are a violation of
sanctions. So I think that would be a very specific concern."
</P>
<P>
"We also believe that diplomatic contacts (with Libya) ought
to be maintained at a low level, and we would be disappointed
with the visit of any head of state."
</P>
<P>
But South African Foreign Ministry spokesman Peter Swanepoel
said Mandela's visit to Libya would not violate UN Sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will travel to Tripoli from southern Tunisia by road.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel said: "the president won't be breaking any
sanctions, he's not flying in and out."
</P>
<P>
He said that nor the visit would affect South Africa's
relations with Washington.
</P>
<P>
The South African government is well aware of the position of
the United States, but South Africa also has bilateral ties with
Libya, which is a fellow member of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
"Through the (U.S.-South Africa) Bilational Commission we keep
one another informed of our different positions," Swanepoel said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations banned flight to Libya after Tripoli's
refusal to extradite two suspects for the 1988 bombing of a Pan
Am airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland. The bombing killed 270
people.
</P>
<P>
Obviously in response to Washington's comments on Mandela's
visit, the ANC statement said: "Solutions to international
problems and Africa in particular cannot be based on views of a
few countries, but should allow all countries of the world
including South Africa to contribute meaningfully towards their
resolution."
</P>
<P>
South Africa has insisted on developing relations with Libya,
Iran and Cuba, defying pressure from Washington, which is South
Africa's biggest donor.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is scheduled to visit Libya and Egypt on his way to a
Commonwealth meeting of heads of government in Edingburg,
Scotland on October 24-27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
