<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Launches Anti-TB Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Ruling Zanu (PF)
today launched its anti-tuberculosis campaign when the disease
has manifested itself as the country's major problem with 36,000
new cases recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Launching the campaign here under the theme " Tuberculosis is
preventable and curable, let us join the fight against TB", Oppah
Rushesha, party secretary for health said, " These are indeed
depressing statistics, especially when we are told that TB is
preventable and curable. Clearly there is a problem. Why are the
cases continuing to rise? "
</P>
<P>
While the HIV/AIDS pandemic has had an impact on the rise in
new cases, Rushesha said it should not be so as TB in an
HIV-infected person was curable.
</P>
<P>
" We all have a role to play in the fight against TB. This is
not the responsibility of the Ministry of Health. We as political
leaders must join the fight against TB," Rushesha said.
</P>
<P>
Politicians could contribute in the fight against the disease
by being role models for behavioral change in order to reduce the
HIV epidemic which is fueling the TB problem, she said.
</P>
<P>
There was also need to assist the medical fraternity with the
directly observed treatment, short course (dots) to enhance the
cure rate and decrease infection, she said.
</P>
<P>
Improved housing, sanitation and nutrition, could also help in
containing the TB epidemic, Rushesha said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
