<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somalis Press for Solution to Mass Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The mass deportation of
Somalis by the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia has been felt in
the Somali capital with strong reactions coming from various
civil societies and local human rights organization.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, the local human rights organization,
Ismail Jumale Human Rights Center, said it has been terrified and
condemned the Saudi Arabian security forces for what they called
their inhumane and degrading acts committed against the Somalis
in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
According to the center, the Saudi security forces have begun
what they called a collective punishment by cutting off both
electricity and water in the areas where the Somalis live.
</P>
<P>
The center whose condemnation was prompted by Somalis who
gathered outside their place in north Mogadishu Friday said
women, children and the elderly have been affected by the
collective punishment imposed by Saudi Arabia on the Somalis when
there's no government who would speak on behalf of them at this
crucial moment.
</P>
<P>
Among the crowd that gathered outside the human rights center
were victims of torture in Saudi prisons, mal-nourished people
and others who caught different sickness in the Saudi jails.
</P>
<P>
The center said they have also received deported school
children who were caught in the streets of Jeddah as they came
back from school to their home and were deported straight to
Somalia without the knowledge of their parents.
</P>
<P>
According to the human rights center, more than 3,200 deported
people from Saudi Arabia have reached here in Somalia and the
last deportee that arrived at Ballidogle Airport, 90 km southwest
of the capital, included a woman who died on the way inside the
airplane.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi security personnel have also collected women who
just gave birth at the hospitals for deportation, while their
other children and husbands were left behind, the center noted.
</P>
<P>
The human rights center also expressed concern over the fate
of thousands of Somalis who are now stranded in the dessert in an
attempt to escape the security forces and others who are still
absconding.
</P>
<P>
The center has proposed that the Saudi authorities should come
up with planes to cope with the crises regarding the Somalis and
their human rights be respected.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the international community, the Arab
League, international watch dog organizations and regional
organizations to give the Somalis a special consideration when
there isn't a government to represent their interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Launches Tourism Promotion Campaign in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan delegation left
here today for a week-long tourism sales, marketing and
promotional campaign in Europe in a bid to stem further drop in
tourist bookings.
</P>
<P>
The delegation composed of representatives from government
departments and the private sector is scheduled to visit Germany,
Italy, Switzerland and France.
</P>
<P>
During the past two months, violent actions in
the tourist resort of Mombasa and its environs which claimed
more than 60 lives had led to massive cancellation of tourist
bookings on the overseas market.
</P>
<P>
As a result, coastal hotels in the violence affected areas
suffered an unprecedented drop in bed occupancy rates which
declined from a peak of 80-90 percent to a record low of 0-25
percent.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the delegation led by
Permanent Secretary of the Ministry of Tourism and
Wildlife S.M. Mbova is designed to arrest further decline in tourist
bookings.
</P>
<P>
Local press attributed the sharp drop to the consistent
reports by west media that the East African country was not a
safe travel destination.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will meet with key tour operators, travel
agents, charter flight operators and media representatives and
tell them Kenya was safe.
</P>
<P>
The team will also seek to reassure European tourists that
calm had been restored and life returned to normal in Mombasa and
its environs.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is Kenya's biggest foreign exchange earner with 493
million U.S. Dollars fetched last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
