<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Reiterates Commitment to OPEC's Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) today reiterated its commitment to the oil output quota of
some 2.2 million barrels per day (bpd) set by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued today, UAE's Minister of Petroleum
and Mineral Resources Obeid bin Saif Al Nasir said that his
country, an important OPEC member, would not ask for higher
production ceiling unless the majority of other OPEC members do
so.
</P>
<P>
He said that the OPEC member states have reached consensus to
maintain the current oil output ceiling during last June's
meeting and any new development in the field will be discussed
at the next meeting due in November.
</P>
<P>
The current OPEC ceiling, which was set in September 1993 with
the exception of Iraq's, stands at 25.03 million bpd and has
remained unchanged since then.
</P>
<P>
However, OPEC's reports show that the actual output now is
running nearly 2 million barrels a day in excess of the
ceiling because many members are known to have been exceeding
their quotas.
</P>
<P>
The UAE oil minister called on the OPEC producers to
conscientiously maintain their oil production quotas to shore up
oil prices and stablize the world crude market. "This would
benefit themselves," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
