<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merger Wave Knocks at US Accounting Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The merger wave which has
recently swept across several industries of the United States and
Europe is likely to hit two major U.S. accounting and consulting
firms, creating the world's largest accounting company.
</P>
<P>
KPMG and Ernst &AMP; Young, already the world's giants in the
industry, are expected to merge into a business with a combined
revenue of 15.3 billion U.S. dollars and 11,712 partners, the New
York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
With this deal, said to be announced next week, "the Big Six"
accounting firms in the U.S., a result of the merger from "the Big
Eight" in the late 1980s, will become "the Big Four" if the
September announcement of another merger of two accounting firms
is taken into account.
</P>
<P>
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand and Price Waterhouse are discussing to become
one with revenue expanding to 11.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two merger plans unvealed in a relatively short period
involve a total revenue of over 27 billion dollars, or 62 percent
of the total "Big Six."
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the merger action shows the efforts the accounting
firms are making to seek ways of reducing costs and expanding
international operations in a globalization trend which also
affects the services industry.
</P>
<P>
U.S. accounting firms are reporting slowing business on their
traditional lines and auditing has become fiercely competitive.
</P>
<P>
U.S. accounting businesses have largely gone abroad, but they
want to stride more rapidly by forming stronger alliances.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the current "Big Six" have a combined
overseas revenue of 25.66 billion dollars, against 17.4 billion
dollars for the U.S. market, at already a six to four ratio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
