<HEADLINE> Jordan, Bahrain to Set up High-Level Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Bahrain today
decided to establish a joint committee to strengthen their ties,
the Bahraini news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It said that Bahrain's Foreign Minister Sheikh Mohammed bin
Mubarak al-Khalifa and visiting Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez
Tarawneh agreed to set up the committee which would be led by
prime ministers of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed bilateral relations and agreed to further
exchange high-level visits in order to boost coordination between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh arrived in Bahrain today for a two-day visit which
was considered part of Jordan's efforts to improve its relations
with Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's relations with the Gulf states were cut off due to
the kingdom's support for Iraq during the Gulf War crisis caused
by Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
But Jordan's ties with the Gulf states have been improved in
recent years as Jordan distanced itself from Iraq. In the past
years, Jordan has sent many senior officials to make diplomatic
shuttles in the oil-rich region. King Hussein of Jordan has also
visited some Gulf states in recent years. 
