<HEADLINE> Egypt: Harassment Against its Ambassador Must Stop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foregin Minister Amr
Moussa said today the alleged campaign of harassment against
Egypt's Ambassador to Israel Mohammed Bassiouni must stop.
</P>
<P>
"Such provocations should not happen again," Moussa told
reporters. He is expected to raise the issue during a lightning
visit to Israel to take part in the opening of the Middle East
Peace Institute Monday.
</P>
<P>
But when assessing the issue, Moussa said, Egypt will take into
consideration the Israeli official apology for the alleged
harassment against Bassiouni.
</P>
<P>
Moussa has met with Bassiouni after the latter returned home
Monday for a short stay. Bassiouni, who has served as Egypt's top
diplomat to Israel for 17 years, complained that he has been
bothered by Israeli officials and threatened to go home.
</P>
<P>
He had protested against a series of threatening calls on his
home phone and what he said was a decision by Israeli authorities to
allow a demonstration outside his residence.
</P>
<P>
He also complained that his official car was searched by Israeli
border guards at the Rafah crossing from the Gaza Strip into Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Both Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Foreign
Minister David Levy had spoken to the ambassador to reassure him
that he had their respect and his accusations would be taken
seriously, according to the Middle East Times.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli Foreign Ministry denied there was any
official harassment of Bassiouni and expressed "regrets" over the
Rafah incident.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's visit comes at the invitation of former Israeli prime
minister Shimon Peres, who is the founder of the peace institute.
</P>
<P>
The visit "testifies to Egypt's adherence to peace and keenness
on pushing forward the peace-advocate trend inside Israel," Moussa
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that he will hold a number of meetings during his
few-hour visit to Israel without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with the
Jewish state and has played a significant role in mediating the
Israeli-Arab peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
