<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Moves for Fresh Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has reacted to a call by west African foreign ministers for
fresh talks on resolving the country's crisis since the May 25
coup that ousted the legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
A junta spokesman said on Friday that the foreign minister of
the military regime, Alimamy Paolo Bangura, would lead a
delegation to neighboring Guinea next Wednesday to meet his west
African counterparts on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, foreign ministers from Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea,
Liberia and Cote d'Ivoire, mandated by west African leaders to
handle the crisis, expressed their willingness to resume dialogue
with junta on peaceful settlement of the crisis in the country on
some conditions.
</P>
<P>
The previous dialogue broke down in July when the junta said
it needed four years to quit.
</P>
<P>
It seems that this time the junta is still reluctant to an
immediate hand-over to the ousted civilian government as required
by the United Nations which announced sanctions early this month.
</P>
<P>
Announcing next week's meeting with west African foreign
ministers, the junta spokesman said, "we are asking the UN and
rest of the international community to give us a transition
period during which we can organize fresh elections."
</P>
<P>
"We are assured of our security at the talks because the UN,
Commonwealth and Organization of African Unity will be sending
observers," Alliu Kamara said, quoted by a report reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), which
embraces Sierra Leone, has imposed sanctions against the junta
since the coup, while holding talks with the coupists.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member sub-regional body also warned of possible use of
force to oust the junta if dialogue and sanctions fail.
</P>
<P>
Following the UN sanctions, ECOWAS foreign ministers gave
their conditions for resumed talks that representatives of the
illegal regime led by Major Johnny Paul Koroma must have
requisite mandate to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also demanded that the regime must negotiate in
good faith.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the negotiations should strictly be within the
mandate of ECOWAS and the UN Security Council, which focuses on
the junta's immediate quit and return power to the ousted
legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
The call was followed by repeated clashes between the junta
and ECOWAS peacekeepers, which reached a new peak with the
country's telecommunications facilities and radio and television
stations in the capital Freetown damaged over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
As a result, hundreds of people fled Freetown and more are
expected to flee if next Wednesday's dialogue fails.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
