<HEADLINE> Lebanon Calls for Establishing Arab Common Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
called on Arab countries today to boost economic cooperation and
establish an Arab common market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the 7th Arab Businessmen
and Investors' Conference here, Hrawi said that the Arab world
should step up economic cooperation to protect their interests in
the region and in the world.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that the proposal to establish an Arab
common market was put forward 33 years ago, but it was still being
discussed today.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference to promote Arab integration, which was
first held in 1982, was hosted by the 22-member Arab League, the
Federation of Arab Chambers of Commerce and Industry and the Arab
Investment Insurance Organization.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 delegates, including ministers from Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Jordan, Egypt, Tunisia and Sudan, are taking part in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi urged Arab investors and businessmen to make greater
efforts to achieve this goal as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that Lebanon would boycott the Middle East and
North Africa Economic Conference due to be held in Qatari capital
Doha in mid-November, which Israel has been invited to attend.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said Lebanon, together with Syria, were using
the opportunity to discourage other Arab countries from
participating the Doha conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
