<HEADLINE> Bankruptcies in California Slow Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELOS, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of Californians
seeking shelter from their debts declined in the third quarter,
breaking a nearly four-year string of soaring bankruptcies, a
research firm reported here today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50,650 personal bankruptcies were filed statewide in
the July-September period, 5.5 percent below filings in the second
quarter, according to statistics released by CDB Infotek in Los
Angelos.
</P>
<P>
The California figures follow the release earlier this week of
a report showing that personal bankruptcies nationwide also
decreased. A total of 335,218 people sought Bankruptcy Court
protection in the United States in the third quarter. That was
down 4 percent from the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts believe the new numbers indicate that an
improving economy and continued job growth are at last having a
positive effect on how households manage their debts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economy entered its seventh year of unbroken growth --
its third-longest expansion since World War II, while its jobless
rate has been decreasing during the past four years.
</P>
<P>
However, personal bankruptcies in California as well as in this
country had doubled from the end of 1993 to this year's second
quarter, a phenomenon attributed to increasing debt loads and the
growing social acceptance of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, people seeking bankruptcy protection
have found it far easier to receive more credit after filing. Many
lenders have pushed to reform the nation's Bankruptcy Code to make
it more difficult for borrowers to shield certain assets from
creditors.
</P>
<P>
A federally appointed panel, the National Bankruptcy Review
Commission, on Monday will present its package of proposed changes
to Congress and the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Local Governments Act Against Genetic Bias </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 18 (Xinhua) -- An individual's genetic
information could be misused by the insurance company and many
U.S. states are outlawing such a practice.
</P>
<P>
These states have found that some insurance and health firms
are requiring or using genetic information to deny coverage or
increase premiums of those people predisposed to develop a cancer
or other illnesses, the New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
At least 26 states have passed laws to prevent such instances
from happening, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Some of these states have authorized criminal penalties or
lawsuits for damages following the unauthorized disclosure of
genetic information.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have complained that the Federal Government
acts "too slowly" in protecting the confidentiality of individual
genetic information.
</P>
<P>
A number of congressmen argue that they did not take
legislative action because they fear that it may hinder genetic
research and clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
At least one state has passed law defining genetic information
as personal property. Citing Oregon as an example, the Times said
some researchers and drug makers are seeing such a law
"premature." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
