<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Plans to Expand Gas Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia is planning
to widen exploitation of natural gas to devote this natural
resource as the engine of domestic industrial growth, a senior
Saudi official said today.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Industry and Electricity Minister Hashim Yamani made the
remarks while inaugurating a three-day seminar in Saudi western
coast city of Yanbou, which is aimed at searching for investment
opportunities in the gas sector and modern technology, according
to the Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Yamani said his country was determined to use its wealth of
natural gas and use it locally, adding that his ministry would
increase depending on natural gas energy to increase production
of electricity power.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his country needs 137 billion U.S. dollars
to launch energy and petrochemical projects until the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has a gas reserve of 204 trillion cubic feet,
accounting for about 3.9 percent of the world gas reserves.
