<HEADLINE> Egypt: Attendance of Doha Conference Depends on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's participation in the
fourth Middle East and North Africa economic conference hinges on
whether or not a headway will be made in the Mideast peacemaking,
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said today.
</P>
<P>
"By headway, we do not mean the form which involves meetings
and handshakes but rather by this we mean success on all axes
especially the Palestinian track," Moussa said in statements to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"In more general words by progress, we mean how much Israel
is delivering on its previous and present promises regarding the
peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Moussa said the Israeli practices left little to be
optimistic about the economic conference slated for November
16-18 in the Qatari capital of Doha.
</P>
<P>
"I regret to say that the majority in Egypt, in the area and
outside it feel pessimistic about the peace process," he said,
commenting on Israel's declaration that it will not hand over
more land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu made the statement
hours before the arrival to the region by U.S. Mideast peace
coordinator Dennis Ross to advance the peace process that
jump-started after a seven-month freeze.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said there are some U.S. initiatives to bring
Palestinians and Israelis to talk together but Cairo has to wait
and see.
</P>
<P>
"But as everybody is pessimistic and casts doubts on the
possibility of reaching tangible results, the most prevailing
words at present are that these meetings are useless and to no
avail," he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has denied U.S. State Department reports that
U.S. received pledges from a number of Arab countries, including
Egypt, to take part in the conference and linked its
participation in a shift of the Israeli policy toward the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The peace process came to a halt in March after Israel
obstinately went ahead with the building of a Jewish settlement
in Arab East Jerusalem despite world outcry.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab countries have either rejected or threatened to
boycott the Doha conference which is to include Israel. But Qatar
said it expects 82 countries, including 12 Arab countries, at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
As a direct spinoff of the peace process that started in 1991,
the annual MENA conference had been held in Casablanca, Amman and
Cairo since 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
