<HEADLINE> Currency Adjustment to Boost Exports: Pak Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Commerce Minister
Ishaq Dar today defended the government decision of the adjustment
of the country's currency, saying it would boost exports and help
to compete with trading partners.
</P>
<P>
In an interview telecast by Pakistan Television here, Ishaq
said the adjustment of the rupee would not only focus on exports
but also increase GDP (gross domestic product) growth.
</P>
<P>
Ishaq said the devaluation of Pakistan rupee by 8.71 percent,
which was announced by the State Bank of Pakistan last week, would
also bring benefits to agricultural as well as industrial
products.
</P>
<P>
"This decision has been taken in the larger interest of the
country aimed at boosting exports and competing trading partners
actively", he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the adjustment will also reduce the trade gap and help
bring inflation rate to a single digit.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question regarding external pressure to adjust
the currency, the commerce minister categorically rejected such
allegations.
</P>
<P>
The decision was not taken under any pressure from any quarter
but added it was a bold decision of the government to compete in
international market, Ishaq said.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that some external factors forced the
adjustment of the currency but he declined to elaborate on them.
</P>
<P>
If the decision to adjust the currency had not been taken
exports of the country would have gone down, he said, adding
trading competitors including Malaysia, Thailand and Indonesia
devalued their currencies by 20 to 40 percent in the last few
months.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the stability of commodities' prices, he
assured they will remain stable and warned that the exploiters and
black-marketeers would be dealt with an iron hand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
