<HEADLINE> Tajik Opposition Frees 80 Government Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Tajikistan's Islamic opposition
forces released more than 80 government soldiers captured during
the five-year civil war, the Itar-Tass News Agency reported from
Dushanbe, the Tajik capital, today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted the opposition forces chief of staff Davlat
Usmon as saying that the act was a humanitarian action under the
peace agreement, signed by Tajik president Emomali Rakhmonov and
the opposition leader Said Abdullo Nuri in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The servicemen had been held by field commander Mirzo Ziyeyev
during the past two to three years in the Tavil Dara valley about
200 kilometers east of Dushanbe.
</P>
<P>
The freed soldiers and officers on Sunday morning moved from
Tavil Dara to Dushanbe under the convoy of peacekeeping troops and
U.N. military observers.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Tajik opposition forces still hold
about 250 captives at present.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Tajik government decided to free about 170
opposition supporters on October 18-19 under the law of amnesty,
Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
However, the implementation of the peace agreement was put in
doubt after a series of bombings and armed attacks, which killed
18 Tajik soldiers last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
