<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Upsets Kuerten to Win HK Tennis Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Byron Black upset
Brazil's French Open champion Gustavo Kuerten in a marathon-style
final to win the men's singles title of the 722,500 U.S. dollar
1997 Marlboro Tennis Championships in Victoria Park here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Black, 28 and ranked 61st in the world, held world eleven
Kuerten to five sets in a time of three hours and 23 minutes,
before winning 6-3, 6-7 (4-7), 6-2, 3-6, 7-6 (7-5). It was the
first five-set final in the history of the annual event.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten, 21, became the top favorite here after winning the
French Open crown earlier this year in Paris. He qualified for
the final after beating Australian Scott Draper 6-3, 6-4 in the
semi-final here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Black won his final berth after defeating Germany's former
world number one Boris Becker 7-6 (7-3), 6-7 (6-8), 6-4 in the
other semi-final match.
</P>
<P>
In a test mainly of baseline play, it was Black's consistency
and sudden burst of poor temper on the Kuerten's side that finally
brought the thrilling match to Black's favor.
</P>
<P>
After they took one set each, usually cool Kuerten began
murmuring against bad calls that seemed to cost his game in the
third set. After being warned by the referee before the start of
the eighth game, the Brazilian became so upset that he looked
reluctant to retrieve shots on his court.
</P>
<P>
But Kuerten managed to pull himself together after the break
and won the fourth set to level with his opponent two sets to two.
But accurate passing shots and times of net volleys helped Black
to seal the set and the triumph.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that Kuerten was strong in forehand
shots while his opponent benefited much from the backhands. A
surprisingly high rate of unforced errors including unsuccessful
net play attempts damaged Kuerten's chances.
</P>
<P>
In a later final today, Thomas Johansson and Mikael Tillstrom
from Sweden defeated Black and American Jonanthan Stark 3-6, 6-3,
7-6 (10-8) to take the doubles title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
