<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, October 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya announced his
resignation today after four months in office. He said at a press
conference that he would remain at his post until a forthcoming
cabinet reshuffle completes and his successor is appointed, so as
to avoid disruption of work at his ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said he had informed Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh of
his decision.
</P>
<P>
He did not say why he had decided to resign, but it is believed
that he was not happy with Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh,
who revoked a petrol and diesel oil tax hike by one baht per
liter, which Thanong had announced only three days before, on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thanong was in favor of an oil tax hike to earn more national
revenue and to meet the demand of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) for a budget surplus of 1 percent of gross domestic product
in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A senior Palestinian National Authority (PNA) official
today expressed hope that U.S Mideast peace coordinator Dennis
Ross could force Israel to abide by signed agreements on his new
mediation bid.
</P>
<P>
"I hope Ross would carry with him a mechanism that could force
Israel to abide by an exact and accurate implementation of the
signed agreements with the Palestinians," PNA Minister of Local
Government Saeb Erekat said in an interview with Voice of Arabs
radio over telephone from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Ross is returned to the region today, 10 days after he
successfully persuaded Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and PNA President Yasser Arafat to meet on October 8, their first
direct talks in eight months.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy is likely to meet Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy and senior PLO negotiator Mahmoud Abbas in advance of their
scheduled Washington meeting on October 27.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- One Israeli soldier was killed and two others
lightly hurt Saturday evening when their tank was hit by an
anti-tank missile fired by Hezbollah gunmen in South Lebanon,
Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the incident occurred in the norther eastern
sector of the Israeli-proclaimed South Lebanon Security
Zone. Hezbollah gunmen fired an anti-tank missile which hit
directly the tank and wounded the three soldiers inside, one of
them died from wounds after being evacuated to a hospital in Safed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another Israeli soldier died in Haifa's Ramban
Hospital from the wounds he suffered in South Lebanon two months
ago. He was shot by a comrade from his own unit during an ambush
mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
