<HEADLINE> US Airline Opens Service Facilities in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 19 (Xinhua) -- United Airlines, one of the
leading airlines in the United States, has opened its first
overseas industrial service facility in Beijing as part of an
effort to expand its involvement in China's surging aviation
market.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing branch of UAL Services, United's service division,
will provide "comprehensive services to airline companies,
including maintenance, ground service, flight training, parts and
equipment sales and other business services and consulting,"
according to Bruce Sweigert, general manager of UAL Services in
China.
</P>
<P>
United has participated in a number of long-term cooperative
programs with several small- to medium-sized Chinese airlines,
including Xinhua Airlines, Xiamen Airlines and Hainan
Airlines. United has provided both pilot training and ground
services.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to working with the Civil Aviation
Administration of China (CAAC) and Chinese airlines to help
develop the country's aviation industry," said Sweigert, "We are
excited about having the opportunity to work in such a dynamic
important market."
</P>
<P>
United Airlines is currently negotiating with the Chinese
partners for opening joint air routes between the US and inland
provinces.
</P>
<P>
United's engineering and maintenance support network is amongst
the largest in the world, with three heavy maintenance centers
based in San Francisco, Oakland and Indianapolis. The centers
completes over 600 airframe and 600 engine overhauls, and replaces
1.5 million aircraft components annually.
</P>
<P>
United and Northwestern Airlines are only two authorized US
carriers operating air routes between US and Chinese cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
