<HEADLINE> Social Development Continues to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 19 (Xinhua) -- China's integrated social
development index for 1996 surged by 9.6 percentage points on the
previous year, despite a drop in the unemployment rate
according to a report by the State Statistical Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
The integrated index consists of data on the environment,
population, economy, income distribution, social guarantees,
employment, health care, culture, sports, education and social
security.
</P>
<P>
The index for income distribution rose by the widest margin,
with the annual rate for 1996 standing at 23 percent. The index
for social security ranked second with a growth rate of 19 percent
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that employment, the only area with negative
growth, dropped 11 percent when compared to the corresponding
figure in 1995. Over 5.52 million people were unemployeed at the
end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts further noted that the structure of employment improved
somewhat last year, with more farmers going to work for township
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the report indicated that China's coastal regions
continue to lead the country in social development.
</P>
<P>
However, central and western regions recorded accelerated
growth in social development in 1996, with respective growth rates
of 6.9 percent and 10.6 percent. The rate for the eastern region
stood at four percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
