<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea Makes Further Efforts to Stimulate Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korea, in a struggling
effort to shore up stock prices, came out with a package of
measures to stabilize the ailing stock market today, which calls
for the expansion of tax favors to stock investors.
</P>
<P>
The measures are mainly focused on tax cuts for foreign
investors, promising benefits for long-term stock investors to
curb massive stock sell-offs and tax cuts for those who invest in
venture funds run by investment trust companies.
</P>
<P>
The government announced its first long-term stock market
boosting measures on October 13, but failed to prevent the
continued drop of stock prices.
</P>
<P>
The Seoul stock market has suffered sharp declines with the
composite stock price index plummeting to 584.71 over the weekend,
the lowest point in five years.
</P>
<P>
Measures to be taken this time are expected to stop the
plummeting share prices at least for now, market observers
projected.
</P>
<P>
However, they added the brakes will not be on for long unless
the negative factors still affecting the market, such as political
unrest and financial turmoil, are pacified.
</P>
<P>
The continuing lack of liquidity in funding institutions,
coupled with the worst financial crisis South Korea has seen in
recent years, had prompted fears of back-to-back bankruptcies of
large business groups and their affiliate firms for quite some
time.
</P>
<P>
The market was also largely influenced by outside factors such
as the slush-fund allegations launched by the ruling New Korea
Party against the opposition presidential candidate Kim Dae-jung,
market analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
