<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Finance Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Thanong
Bidaya announced his resignation here tonight at his residence
after exactly four months in office.
</P>
<P>
He said at a press conference that he would remain at his post
until a forthcoming cabinet reshuffle completes and his successor
is appointed, so as to avoid disruption of work at his ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said he had informed Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh of
his decision.
</P>
<P>
He did not say why he had decided to resign, but it is believed
that he was not happy with Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh,
who revoked a petrol and diesel oil tax hike by one baht per
liter, which Thanong had announced only three days before, on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thanong was in favor of an oil tax hike to earn more national
revenue and to meet the demand of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) for a budget surplus of 1 percent of gross domestic product
in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister on Saturday told a rally in a
northeastern province that the oil tax hike had affected the
people's life and was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
Some mass organizations had planned to stage demonstrations to
demand the prime minister's resignation.
</P>
<P>
Thanong, a non-MP and president of the Military Bank, had been
invited by the prime minister to succeed Amnuay Virawan, who
resigned on June 19.
</P>
<P>
Since the Chavalit government took office in December last
year, the government has had two finance ministers, who had
followed different financial policies.
</P>
<P>
Amnuay refused to unpeg the baht from the US dollar and spent
several billion dollars to rescue the baht at offshore money
markets when the baht was under pressure to devalue, while
Thanong, only 13 days after he became finance minister, decide to
float the baht, and requested assistance from the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Since July 2 the baht has depreciated by about 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, local television reported that the
prime minister was holding a meeting with leaders of five other
coalition parties to discuss a cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that if the prime minister decides to have a
reshuffle, ministers and vice ministers in charge of economic
affairs will be affected, so as to improve the country's
macroeconomic and financial administration.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
