<HEADLINE> Chinese Grain Importer Confident About Sino-US Trade (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Mingchen, president of the
China National Cereals, Oils and Foodstuffs Import and Export
Corporation (COFCO), said that there exist new opportunities for
US agricultural products to share a bigger part in Chinese market,
which will help create a long-term and stable environment of
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, also a member of the delegation that will accompany
President Jiang Zemin on a state visit to the U.S. later this
month, noted that U.S. wheat now accounts for more than a third of
China's annual wheat imports, and China also imports a large
amount of soybeans, barley, and other grains from the US every
year, or about 8 to 9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fierce competition in the world grain market, China
has always been one of the major buyers of the US agricultural
products, with orders on 89.38 million tons of American grain
since 1972, worth about 13.4 billion US dollars, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
The grain imports have played an important role in reducing the
U.S. trade deficit with China and have helped create jobs in the
U.S., and they have also had a favorable impact on US grain
growing and the reduction of stockpiles, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' agriculture departments have negotiated
obstacles to trade, such as TCK, a wheat disease found in US wheat
shipments to China, and the China National Cereals, Oils and
Foodstuffs Import and Export Corporation (COFCO) has established
links with many grain grower associations, food processing
companies, and congressmen from grain growing areas in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Food co-operation has even gone beyond grain imports and
exports. the COFCO has set up a joint edible-oil venture with the
U.S.'s ADM in the city of Zhangjiagang in east China's Jiangsu
Province, and "This is just the beginning," Zhou said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
