<HEADLINE> Fuzhou's Foreign-funded Firms Are Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 5,100 foreign-funded
enterprises have been approved for Fuzhou, capital city of east
China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
These enterprises involve a total overseas investment of 13.2
billion U.S. dollars, with 5 billion U.S. dollars already put to
use.
</P>
<P>
According to Gong Xiong, vice-mayor of the city, some 2,500
foreign-funded enterprises have started business.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that industrial output and exports of the joint
ventures, co-operative enterprises and wholly foreign-funded ones
have accounted for 60 percent and 80 percent of the city's total,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
These ventures achieved 20 billion U.S. dollars of industrial
output in 1995, double the figure for 1993. The foreign-funded
enterprises that have gone into operation have generated 6.5
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports by these ventures reached 1.5 billion U.S. dollars in
1996, some 10 times more than in 1991, and accounted for 85
percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded enterprises have become the backbone of the
city's five pillar industries, namely, electronic and
machine-building industry, textiles, chemicals, building materials
and aquatic products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
