<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Swimming Record Holders Overturned at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 19 (Xinhua) -- World record holders Le Jingyi
and Liu Limin were overturned on the last day of the swimming
competition at the Chinese Eighth National Games here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Le, who holds the world 50 and 100 meters freestyle records,
was beaten by Shan Ying of the Chinese Army in the 50m event.
</P>
<P>
Shan, 19, won the gold with 24.71 seconds, 0.17 second ahead of
Le, who won the 100 meters title early. The third place went to
Shanghai's Ye Peipei with 25.44 seconds.
</P>
<P>
This was a repeat of Le's loss at the Atlanta Olympic Games,
where she captured the gold in the 100m while let the 50m slip off
her hands.
</P>
<P>
Liu Limin of Hubei, world record holder in the short-course
100m butterfly, finished a distance fourth place in the women's
200m butterfly.
</P>
<P>
Qu Yun of the Chinese Army took the event with a year-best time
of 2:08.10, followed by Hu Ning of Liaoning with 2:08.34.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yanyan of Guangxi, who broke the world 200m individual
medley record on Thursday, finished third with 2:10.45.
</P>
<P>
"She has made rapid progress recently and has the calibre to
challenge the world record holder Le," said Le's coach Zhou Ming,
also deputy head coach of the Chinese national team.
</P>
<P>
Zhou added that the Shanghai native badly wanted to win the
gold. "Her aim is to win the gold, the second is to break her own
world record."
</P>
<P>
Shan, who beat Le in the 100m event but flopped in the 100m at
the Olympic trials in April, 1996, said the key to victory is an
upperhand she enjoyed in the start.
</P>
<P>
Qu Yun, also gold medalist in the 200m buttfly in the seventh
National Games four years ago, fell to a slump in the past two
years. "This might be a turnpoint for me," she said.
</P>
<P>
Qu had expected Liu Limin will be her top challenger in the
day's competition. "She is the best butterfly swimmer in China,
but I don't know why she slipped to the fourth," Qu said.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 200m backstroke, Fu Yong of Shandong set an Asian
record of 1:58.72 to capture the gold, while his fellow Jin Hao
completed a gold double in the 1,500m freestyle with 15:36.65
following his victory in the 400m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
The final swimming gold of the National Games was won by the
local foursome in the men's 4X100m team medley relay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
