<HEADLINE> Pakistan Considers Foreign Exchange Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMBAD, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Local and foreign banks
operating in Pakistan have called on the government to launch a
two-year US dollar-denominated bond as part of a multi-dimensional
foreign exchange reforms in the country, officials said.
</P>
<P>
A high-level committee headed by Mahfooz Alam, chief foreign
exchange advisor of the State Bank of Pakistan, is busy working
out specifics of the proposed bond, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which consists of representatives from a number
of local and foreign banks, has asked the banks to submit their
views on the introduction of such a bond and other proposed
reforms, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
"Once the committee has received all the suggestions it would
weigh their pros and cons and see what is worth implementing,"
they said.
</P>
<P>
Most senior bankers have suggested that the launching of the
bond would come as part of a multi-dimensional foreign exchange
reforms and not as a solitary step, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, no deadline has been fixed for the implementation of
the reforms, but some of the reforms may take effect during this
fiscal year, the officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
