<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improving the Quality of Chinese Citizens (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The editorial says that China faces the imperative and
significant task of improving the quality of the people in line
with the dramatic development of science and technology, as well
as the increasingly fierce competition in the area of integrated
national power, as the global focus is now on peace and develop.
</P>
<P>
The key to improving the quality of the people is to constantly
educate both cadres and the people in the Deng Xiaoping Theory,
while at the same time establishing clear targets and building the
confidence of the people as they strive for the common ideal.
</P>
<P>
"Deng Xiaoping Theory is the source of our spirit and power,"
according to the editorial, which emphasizes that following the
guidance of the theory is the only way China can march forward
with a correct orientation and build the nation into a prosperous,
strong, democratic and civilized socialist country with the
efforts of several generations.
</P>
<P>
Improving the quality of the people will require ethical and
cultural progress focused on ideology and morality, the editorial
continues.
</P>
<P>
The current conditions of reform, opening up and developing a
socialist market economy makes it especially important to advocate
patriotism, collectivism and socialism, as well as the concept of
serving the people, according to the editorial.
</P>
<P>
It urges expanded education related to public morality,
professional ethics and family virtue in order to ensure that
people establish personal relationships based on unity, mutual
assistance, equality, friendship and common progress.
</P>
<P>
Cultural sectors, including the literary, arts, press,
publications, and broadcast, film and television sectors, should
be developed.
</P>
<P>
The editorial stresses the importance of education, and science
and technology which fuel the country's economic development, and
notes that the rejuvenation of the country will depend heavily on
educated and talented people.
</P>
<P>
The editorial calls for placing priority on developing the
educational sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
