<HEADLINE> Weekly Review on Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Most of the heavy-weighted
shares on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) rallied smartly to lift
the Sensitive Index (Sensex) by nearly 49 points during the week
thanks to sustained buying by speculators and sizable purchases by
foreign institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
The sentiment was further aided by Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram's reported assurance that the Indian government would
unveil special policy initiatives to address the problems of the
domestic manufacturing sector to spurt the sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
The BSE Sensex rose sharply to end the week at 4,106.26 as
against the last weekend close of 4,057.37, netting a gain of
48.89 points. The BSE-100 index rose by 22.32 points to close the
week at 1,768.48 from the previous weekend close of 1,746.16.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the Dollex were quoted up at 395.24 and 181.78
at the weekend compared with the preceding weekend close of 388.64
and 178.45 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The volume of business during the week spurted to 50.16 billion
rupees (about 1.43 billion U.S. dollars) from last week's turnover
of 45.06 billion rupees (about 1.29 billion dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
