<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Visiting World Bank President
James. D. Wolfensohn today said the institution will continue to
extend every possible support to the Pakistani government to
ameliorate the lot of the poor.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn, who is on a five-day official visit to Pakistan,
made the remarks when he was visiting a tube-well development
program in a village near Lahore, capital of Pakistan's eastern
Punjab province.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government, with the help of the World Bank, is
working on a plan to improve the irrigation system which includes
the bricklining of canals and other water courses, Wolfensohn was
quoted as saying by the Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the World Bank's support for the rural uplift
plans in Pakistan, saying it is preparing a plan for micro credits
and more credits for industrialization.
</P>
<P>
He said he is aware that the people of Pakistan need help in
education, health, roads, macro credits and several other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is already studying the means and ways to fund
the establishment of small industrial units in rural areas, he
said.  
