<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interpol Tries to Check International Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 19 (Xinhua) -- A concerted effort has been
launched by the International Criminal Police Organization
(Interpol) to check international money laundering, Interpol
Secretary General Raymond E. Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
According to Press Trust of India (PTI) today, Kendall said in
an interview with PTI that international money laundering is
"currently one of the most worrying forms of international crime."
</P>
<P>
However, lack of proper legislation in a fair number of
countries and differences in legal, political and law enforcement
systems make the task difficult, said Kendall, who was here to
attend an international conference of Interpol held in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Fraudulent commercial operations are conducted by people
ranging from legitimate businessmen trying to evade taxes to drug
traffickers and smugglers trying to send money abroad, especially
to tax heavens through illegal channels, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that distinction should be made between tax evasion
and laundering of proceeds of crime.
</P>
<P>
"We are launching an attack on organized crime and the most
effective way to deal with it is to take away its financial
back-up," Kendall stated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
