<HEADLINE> Singapore's Retail Sales Record Double-Digit Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's retail sales
index declined by 10.8 percent in August over July this year, the
Government Department of Statistics said today, attributing the
fall to lower consumer spending after the month-long Great
Singapore Sale which ended on July 27, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Statistics said that all activities, with
exception of general provision and sundry shops, encountered sales
declines in August over July, as textiles, wearing apparel and
personal effects fell by 21.4 percent, furniture and household
equipment, by 14 percent, and motor vehicles by 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, it noted that compared to August 1996, the overall
retail sales index in August this year remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The overall catering trade index at current prices in August
this year rose slightly by 0.6 percent over the previous month.
The department said that fast food outlets and other catering
establishments registered higher turnover of 3.5 percent and 0.4
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Total retail sales value in August this year was estimated at
2,021 million Singapore dollars (about 1,347 million US dollars),
down from 2,266 million Singapore dollars (about 1,563 million US
dollars) registered in July, the Department of Statistics said.
</P>
</TEXT>
