<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawians Banned to Buy Maize in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 19 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government has
forbidden Malawians from purchasing maize in its backwater
province of Niassa, to protect the interests of the local farmers
and businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Bonifacio Aly, governor of Niassa, the largest province in
Mozambique, said Saturday that proof has showed that some traders
from Malawi are entering into the province to buy maize. Malawi
has been hard hit by drought this year.
</P>
<P>
Niassa, a province with an area of 129,000 square kilometers,
is a province bordering Malawi and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
As no Mozambicans go to buy maize in the province, some
foreign traders, mostly from Malawi, have crossed the border for
the purchase of maize, which is banned by the Mozambican
government.
</P>
<P>
Aly encouraged Mozambican traders to go and purchase maize
in the province and sell it along the border or in Malawi, but
said Malawians are not allowed to do this.
</P>
<P>
He interpreted this as an action to protect the interests of
his countrymen, saying that "police and other institutions there
have been told to enforce more rigid supervision over this."
</P>
<P>
Aly said the decision was made because the land-locked
province turned out 175,000 tons of grain last year, but farmers
have not sold last year's crop off by now when this year's
harvest season is coming soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
