<HEADLINE> Rural Telephone System Expanded in Anhui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Wang Qiang, a kiwi grower in east
China's Anhui Province, had to travel 30 kilometers from his
mountain village to make a phone call to learn about market
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Now, he can make that call from his own house.
</P>
<P>
Farmers now find it much easier to communicate with the outside
world because of the rapid development in rural telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The number of rural telephone subscribers in Anhui has risen to
more than 400,000 in recent years, a remarkable achievement in
this underdeveloped province in eastern China.
</P>
<P>
The province has given priority to improved communications for
rural residents to meet the needs of rapidly developing market
economy, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Programmable telephone networks have been formed in the rural
areas, with a telephone coverage of some 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has further promoted local
telecommunications by diversifying fund-raising sources.
</P>
<P>
Anhui plans to set up a rural telephone network over the next
three years, with a capacity for 1.9 million lines, 1.15 million
phone subscribers and a telephone coverage of 2.2 percent in the
countryside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
