<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accident Kills 67 in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 19 (Xinhua) -- About 67 people died and
over 22 were seriously injured in a motor accident along the
peninsular area, west of Sierra Leone's capital Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Among the dead were a number of children and suckling mothers.
</P>
<P>
Surviving passengers said the vehicle was a haulage vehicle
used to carry passengers and as it was going across a narrow
bridge near York, about 24 miles from the capital, its rear
wheels missed the kerb of the bridge and somersaulted into a
ravine.
</P>
<P>
Medical personnel who took part in the rescue operations said
many of the victims were squeezed to death by bags of rice and
gallons of kerosene which were among the vehicle's cargo.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that most of those who died were living in the
east of the city and were fleeing possible renewed bombing
attacks by Nigerian Alfa jets.
</P>
<P>
Shellings by Nigerian gunners across the Sierra Leone estuary
killed over 13 people in the east last week.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the main Connaught Hospital told Xinhua today, "we
are battling to serve the lives of at least 10 of the seriously
injured."
</P>
<P>
The doctors are joined in the operations by personnel from the
International Committee of the Red Cross and the Sierra Leone Red
Cross.
</P>
<P>
At the city mortuary, anxious relatives with anxious faces
were identifying the corpses.
</P>
<P>
The peninsular area has been little used in the recent past
because of its poor condition but with the closure of the main
highway at Jui, it now remains the only outlet to the interior.
</P>
<P>
It now takes six hours to reach Waterloo which is the
diversion stop for a journey which normally is undertaken in 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
One passenger told Xinhua, "the road is not good but vehicles
are using it all the same. I counted 189 vehicles using the bad
road within a six hour period." 
</P>
