<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Business News in Brief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major business
briefs of Egypt:
</P>
<P>
-- The trade volume between Egypt and the U.S. stood at
more than 2.16 billion U.S. dollars in the first half of the
current year, the Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. enjoyed a trade surplus of 1.399 billion dollars
during the period, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's exports to the U.S. during the period totaled 308.4
million dollars as against the 365 million dollars in the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the drop to the decrease of Egypt's oil
exports to the U.S. in comparison with the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
While Egypt's imports from the U.S. in the January-June period
stood at less than 1.708 billion dollars, up by 24 percent from
the 1.376 billion dollars recorded in the respective period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt exported 38 billion dollars worth of oil over
the past 16 years, the MENA Saturday quoted Egyptian Minister of
Oil Hamdi al-Banbi as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the past 16 years, international oil companies spent more
than 19 billion dollars on oil prospection in Egypt under 179
agreements, resulting in 130 oil findings of crude oil and natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
-- Experiments on oil recycling started here Saturday by
Egypt Oil and Egypt Oil Cooperative Companies, MENA reported.
</P>
<P>
The project costing 175 million Egyptian pounds (51.4 million
dollars) aims at producing 20,000 tonnes of recycled oil every
year.
</P>
<P>
Several Egyptian oil companies have taken part in the project
that aims at rationalizing the use of energy.
</P>
<P>
The recycled oil will be put on sale on the local markets and
used in truck engines.
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt will export 200,000 kantars (9,000 tonnes)
of cotton to China in accordance with agreements signed with
Beijing when an Egyptian delegation under Prime Minister Kamal
El-Ganzouri visited China during an Asian tour in April, MANA
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed
Gowaili as saying that a Chinese delegation is currently visiting
Egypt to discuss cooperation between the two countries in small
and medium size projects and joint marketing firms.
</P>
<P>
These projects include two cement plants in Suez and Northern
Sinai which are scheduled to start production next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
