<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Recovers 1.14 Bln Dollar Overdue Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's banks have recovered
overdue loans worth 50 billion taka (about 1.14 billion U.S.
dollars) in nine months from January to September this year,
well-informed sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 40 billion taka (about 910 million dollars) was
realized in cash while the rest 10 billion taka (about 227 million
dollars) was in other forms.
</P>
<P>
Lutfar Ragnab Sarker, governor of the Bangladesh Bank, central
bank of the country, attributed the recovery of bad loans to the
government's firm commitment to streamline the financial sector
through legal reforms and other means.
</P>
<P>
He identified mismanagement, inefficiency and wasteful
expenditures as main weaknesses of the country's commercial banks,
but said the situation was improving following a number of reform
measures in the financial sector, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of bad loans now stand at 110 billion taka
(about 2.5 billion dollars), while the outstanding loans of big
public sector enterprises amount to 40 billion taka (about 901
million dollars), according to recent reports by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
