<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Uttar Pradesh Government Plunges into Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 19 (Xinhua) -- The state government of Uttar
Pradesh, the largest state in India, today plunged into a serious
political crisis after the Bahujan Samaj Party (BSP) pulled out of
the coalition government led by the Bharatixa Janata Party (BJP)
leader Kalyan Singh, Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
BSP Vice President Miss Mayawati announced her party's decision
at a hurriedly-called news conference in Lucknow, capital of Uttar
Pradesh, saying that she had given a letter to Governor Romesh
Bhandari in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Singh replaced Miss Mayawati as chief minister of Uttar Pradesh
on September 21 as head of a BJP-led coalition government under a
unique power-sharing agreement between the BJP and the BSP.
</P>
<P>
The two parties agreed to rule the state on a six-month
rotation basis following the emergence of a hung state assembly
from the elections held in the state early this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the news conference, Miss Mayawati said the BSP
withdrew from the Kalyan Singh government because its coalition
partner BJP pursued anti-Dalit (an ethnic minority in India)
policies.
</P>
<P>
She criticized the Kalyan Singh government for reversing
decisions taken during her six-month tenure.
</P>
<P>
The former chief minister urged Governor Bhandari to dissolve
the state assembly as the one-month-old Kalyan Singh government
had been reduced to a minority.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the dramatic development, the BJP, the largest
opposition party at the national level, said Singh should be given
an opportunity to prove his government's majority on the floor of
the house.
</P>
<P>
The party complained that it extended full support to Miss
Mayawati's government as per the accord on rotational chief
ministership but the BSP had failed to honor its commitment.
</P>
<P>
The BJP central leadership would meet soon to evolve a strategy
on how to deal with the crisis, a senior BJP leader said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
