<HEADLINE> Post-handover Budget May Please All in HK: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 19 (Xinhua) -- The first post-handover
budget of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of
China will not only be conductive to economic growth but also
satisfy all the population in Hong Kong, a senior official of the
SAR government said.
</P>
<P>
After consulting with provisional legislators on the 1998 draft
budget Saturday, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang Yam-kuen said:
"We want to prove to the rest of the world that we are capable of
producing a very good budget."
</P>
<P>
It will satisfy both the business community and the wider
population here in the SAR, he added. The draft budget will be
presented to the Provisional Legislative Council next February.
</P>
<P>
Tsang told reporters that most of the lawmakers'
recommendations dealt with revenue items -- many calling for
reductions rather than increases in spending -- and said that they
would be carefully considered.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government is managing financial affairs "very
prudently," he.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa's 7.7-billion-HK
dollar expenditure program, announced in his recent inaugural
policy address, was equal to the projected 5 percent growth rate
of the economy.
</P>
<P>
"I would not have any difficulties in meeting the Chief
Executive's expenditure program," Tsang said. "Because the economy
is growing at 5 percent, I would expect the general revenue will
grow at 5 percent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
