<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Air Cargo Throughput Hits Record High in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's air cargo
throughput hit a monthly record high of 151,340 tons in September,
the highest ever monthly total in the 21 years since Hong Kong Air
Cargo Terminals Ltd. (HACTL) was put into operation.
</P>
<P>
September's throughput beat the previous record of 150,070
tons, set in November 1996, by over 1,000 tons, according to
HACTL, Hong Kong's single airport air cargo handling operator.
</P>
<P>
It was 12.5 percent higher than the total for the corresponding
month in 1996, with all the three categories -- export cargo,
import cargo and transshipment goods -- recording increases.
</P>
<P>
Between January and September this year, the company handled
1,221,555 tons of air cargo, 16 percent more than the total for
the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Given the steady and sustained rate of growth for the first
three quarters, the company expected the throughput for the whole
year to reach 1.7 million tons, about 14 percent higher than last
year's.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accusation of S. Leone Junta Reported to UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 19 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has been accused of acts of aggression and intimidation
against civilians and west African peace-keepers in the country
since the announcement of the United Nations sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
published on Friday, Sierra Leone's permanent representative to
the UN James Jonah alleged that the junta had carried out several
attacks on the peace keeping force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Some of the attacks had lasted for several days, it said,
quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
The junta, the envoy said, had also razed down the private
house of ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, while boasting
through its spokesman Allifu Kamara that the action was a
reprisal for ECOMOG's attacks on their military headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Jonah was possibly sent to the UN by Kabbah and he does not
recognize the junta which ousted Kabbah in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
"Any time a civilian is dead, Tejan Kabbah and his supporters
will definitely suffer because they have been crying to the
international community for military intervention," the letter
quoted the junta spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
The letter also said that the junta had shot and wounded a
journalist outside the burnt residence of Kabbah, suspecting that
he was a reporter for a pro-democracy radio station.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the sanctions, the letter quoted the junta as
telling journalists that "as long as we have our natural
resources, like diamond and gold, I can assure you that sanctions
will only affect our poor innocent civilians but not us (the
ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary Council)".
</P>
<P>
There have been attacks and counterattacks between the junta
soldiers and ECOMOG troops since the UN sanction was announced
early this month.
</P>
<P>
Despite the willingness of west African countries to resume
dialogue with the junta, fighting seems to be escalating.
</P>
<P>
The junta reportedly attacks ECOMOG positions both in the
capital Freetown and other major towns, while ECOMOG shelled its
military headquarters, helicopter gunship, telecommunications
installations and radio and television stations.
</P>
<P>
The UN has set up a committee to supervise the implementation
of the sanctions against the junta, which is expected to
facilitate an early resolution of the crisis in the tiny west
African country of 4.5 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
