<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fitz-Gerald Retains World Squash Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Australian Sarah Fitz-Gerald
retained the women's world squash title in Sydney on Sunday by
beating arch-rival and fellow-Australian Michelle Martin.
</P>
<P>
Fitz-Gerald, who won the world championship in Malaysia last
year, outlasted Martin and her home town crowd of 1,500 to win the
one-hour final 9-5, 5-9, 6-9, 9-2, 9-3.
</P>
<P>
"I'm really hoping this helps to get the monkey off my back
because I have not beaten her (Martin) in a major," Fitz-Gerald
said.
</P>
<P>
"She's always beating me, I've beaten her in everything else
except the British Open which is the Wimbledon of squash. This
would probably be the nicest win out of the two world
championships."
</P>
<P>
Fitz-Gerald had beaten Martin in six of their past seven
matches, but Martin blitzed the world champion 3-0 to win her
fifth British Open earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Fitz-Gerald's coach Mike Johnson said his student handled the
pressure better on Sunday than she had at previous major titles.
</P>
<P>
"Sarah was very angry after the third game that she wasn't
competing," Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
"I impressed upon her to keep playing to the back corners and
wait for the opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"She wound herself up and played a good length and when she
showed she was prepared to run down every point Michelle started
to make errors," he added.
</P>
<P>
But the 30-year-old Martin, who was world champion from
1993-95, hasn't given up hope of regaining that mantle.
</P>
<P>
"I've been at the top before and if I break Sarah once it might
happen again ," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
Fitz-Gerald won 10,500 US dollars prize money in Sydney while
Martin took home 6,935 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both players have entered next week's Australian Open in
Melbourne. 
</P>
</TEXT>
