<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ANC Firm on Refusal to Death Penalty: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 19 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) will not change its stance on the
refusal to the restoration of death penalty, ANC spokesman Ronnie
Mamoepa said today.
</P>
<P>
Mamoepa made the remarks in response to Winnie
Madikizela-Mandela's call for referendum on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"We remain convinced that calls for the death penalty do not
accord with the provisions of our new constitution and the ANC
will never entertain such sentiments," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The ANC expresses its confidence in the national crime
prevention strategy as a means of uprooting crime in our society
and to ensure those responsible for crime do face the full might
of the law."
</P>
<P>
According to the Sunday Times newspaper, Madikizela-Mandela,
ex-wife of President Nelson Mandela, said that a referendum
should be held on the death penalty because criminals are getting
off "Scot-free."
</P>
<P>
She reportedly made the call at a recent closed-door meeting
of the party's policy makers in Midrand, a small city between
Johannesburg and Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The former deputy arts minister is eyeing the post of deputy
presidency at the ANC's national congress in December.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, Madikizela-Mandela's spokesman,
Alan Reynolds confirmed Saturday that she told the meeting:
"Crime is running rampant because the criminals are saying they
won't get the death penalty."
</P>
<P>
"Don't we as a democratic country have an obligation to take
this to a referendum?" she asked.
</P>
<P>
Madikizela-Mandela's request may anger Mandela, who said in
1995: "There can be no referendum in this country on this issue.
There can be no reopening of the question of the death sentence."
</P>
<P>
The president repeated his stance in the following years.
</P>
<P>
The ANC refused to re-introduce the death penalty, abolished
at the eve of the 1994 democratic elections on the ground that
the capital punishment was used as a major tool by the apartheid
government to oppress the blacks.
</P>
<P>
But as crimes and violence became all the more worse, more and
more people called for the re-introduction of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics earlier this year, about half of
blacks and more than 60 percent of whites were in favor of the
reinstatement of the death penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
