<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leoneans Want Nigerian Troops out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Sierra Leoneans went
on street on Saturday in capital Freetown, demanding that Nigeria
pulls its troops out and stops its bombing of the city.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian media reported today that the demonstrators carried
banners, reading "UN must stop Nigeria's bombing" and "S. Abacha
(Nigeria's Head of State), hands off Sierra Leone".
</P>
<P>
They marched from the east to the west of the city and later
converged on the national stadium, where they observed one
minute's silence for the 16 persons killed in Thursday's shelling
by Nigerian troops. A list of the victims' names were announced
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is playing a major role in the west Africa
peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) stationed in Sierra Leone to enforce
the sanctions imposed by the U.N. on its military government that
seized power from elected president Tejan Kabbah on May 25.
</P>
<P>
In the last few days, Nigerian warplanes have dropped bombs on
several Freetown targets, including a telecommunications center
and a transmitter of the state radio and TV stations.
</P>
<P>
The military government in Freetown had accused Nigeria of
actually declaring war on Sierra Leone after Nigerians warplanes
bombing its military headquarters on October 8.
</P>
<P>
But Nigeria replied that it is not in a position to declare
war on that country, because it is acting under the banner of the
ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman of Major Johnny Kromah's military
government announced Saturday in Freetown that they will send a
top-level delegation to Guinean capital Conakry for Wednesday's
talks with the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
This will be the second talk between Freetown and the
sub-regional body, which has been demanding that Kromah gives up
his power to ousted president Kabbah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ma's New Protege Threats World Record in 10,000 Meters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 19 (Xinhua) -- The 17-year-old Dong Yanmei
clocked the best of 30:38.09 to win the women's 10,000 meters
title at the Chinese National Games here Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Dong, one of nine disciples of coach Ma Junren in the 25-member
field, broke away from the leading pack in the last four laps at
the signal of her coach who sat in the stands surrounded by the
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Dong's winning timing is clawing close towards the world record
of 29:31.78 set by Ma's former runner Wang Junxia four years ago
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The top three spots were swept by the members of the Ma's
Family as expected from the enthusiastic fans at the newly-built
Shanghai "Barrel" Complex.
</P>
<P>
"These runners are still very young, they are not ready to
break the world record this time," said coach Ma, "we are setting
our sights upon the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney."
</P>
<P>
Dong, born in December 1979, was recruited by coach Ma into his
training camp in early 1995 after world record holder Wang Junxia
broke away in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"I'm glad to win the gold medal, and I wanted to extend thanks
to coach Ma," said the teenager long-distance runner, "without his
scientific training, I can't stand at the top of the podium."
</P>
<P>
"Prior to the competitions, we're not set and also not ready to
break the world record," said Dong Yanmei.
</P>
<P>
Ma's man disciple Sun Ripeng clocked a new national mark of
8:10.46 to win the men's 3,000 meters steeplechase, closing
towards the Asian mark of 8:09.67.
</P>
<P>
"I'm satisfied with Sun's performance by breaking the national
record today," said coach Ma, "yet it's a pity for his failure to
break the Asian mark because he ran a little bit slower in the
third lap."
</P>
<P>
The men's 110-meter hurdles was won by national champion Chen
Yanhao in front of the home fans in 13.41 seconds, beating
national record holder Li Tong to second in 13.64.
</P>
<P>
"My goal was to win the gold medal in an Asian record," said
the 25-year-old sprinter of Shanghai, "and I hoped to make the
breakthugh in the Asian Games."
</P>
<P>
In Sunday morning, Li Zewen of Yuannan province, clocked the
best of 1:20:46 to take the men's 20-km walking title while the
women's 10-km walking gold medal was won by Fan Xiaoling of the
Chinese Army in 43 mintues 47 seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
