<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Supply Namibia With More Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will upgrade its power
supply to neighboring Namibia under an 18-million-U.S.-dollar
agreement signed on Saturday, Sunday Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Energy and Water Development Minister Suresh Desai
signed the accord with Namibian Mines and Energy Minister Andimba
Toivo Ya Toivo at Katima Mulio border town.
</P>
<P>
When the project is completed the 66 kw power line from
Livingstone's Victoria Falls power station in southern Zambia
will be upgraded to 132 kw power line running over 210 kilometers
into Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Namibia has embarked on a very aggressive rural
electrification program which requires more energy from Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"The project is expected to cost 18 million U.S. Dollars, of
which 15 million Dollars will be spent on the Zambian side and
three million Dollars on the Namibian side," Desai said.
</P>
<P>
Toivo Ya Toivo said due to the Caprivi region's distance
from the NamibianCaprivi electricity grid, it will be very
expensive to supply the region from his country's own grid.
</P>
<P>
"In addition the Zambian power system has a surplus of
electricity while the NamibianCaprivi power system is
experiencing a growth in load which will soon catch up and exceed
its generation capacity.
</P>
<P>
"It is, therefore, evident that the economically most viable
option for Namibia to provide the Caprivi Strip with electricity
is to encourage increased electricity trade with our neighbor
Zambia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
