<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economic, Trade Cooperation Delegation Leaves for US (1) Eds: details added </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 19 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of Chinese President
Jiang Zemin's state visit to the United States, a Chinese economic
and trade cooperation delegation left here today for a nine-day
visit to three cities in the United States -- Los Angeles, New
York City and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
Head of the delegation is Zeng Peiyan, vice-minister of the
State Planning Commission, with Sun Zhenyu, vice-minister of
foreign trade and economic cooperation, as its deputy head.
</P>
<P>
Members of the delegation include officials from the State
Planning Commission, Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, Foreign Ministry, Civil Aviation Administration of
China (CAAC), Ministry of Machine-Building Industry, the People's
Bank of China, the Information Office of the State Council, and
executives of some big Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
The principal members of the delegation are Chen Guangyi,
director of the CAAC; Liu Jiyuan, director of the Aerospace
Administration; Lu Fuyuan, vice-minister of Machine-Building
Industry; Wang Yan, general manager of the China National Offshore
Oil Corporation; and Liu Jinlong, general manager of the Huaneng
Group.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Chinese and U.S. companies are expected to
sign economic and trade contracts worth more than 4 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
These contracts involve such deals as China's purchase of
Boeing aircraft, China's import of US chemical fertilizers, crude
oil and thermal power generating equipment.
</P>
<P>
China and U.S. companies also are expected to discuss joint
development of offshore natural gas, and cooperation in auto and
aerospace industries and financial services.
</P>
<P>
Responding to reporters prior to his departure at the airport,
delegation head Zeng Peiyan said that the visit precedes
President Jiang's state visit to the US, showing that the Chinese
government values very much the Sino-US economic and trade
cooperation, and it has taken an active and pragmatic attitude and
has made an unremitting efforts in promoting such cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side hopes to further boost bilateral economic and
trade cooperation through the visit, and lay a sound foundation
for bilateral cooperation in the years to come, he said, and that
contracts to be signed between the two sides will help advance
their respective economies, and create more job opportunities for
the US.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
