<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Backs Local Small Scale Road Builders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 19 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
formulated a deliberate policy to support local small scale road
constructors, Sunday Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Deputy Works and Supply Minister Celestino Chibamba
as saying here Saturday that small scale local road constructors
and consultants will benefit from the recently approved 70
million U.S. Dollars road rehabilitation project funded by the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see small scale road constructors
consultants to take up the challenge and go into the business, we
are giving them priority as we would like the money being given
to us to remain here but that is not to say the bigger
multi-national companies will be completedly discarded.
</P>
<P>
"The contracts for the small scale road constructors will
range from one million Kwacha (770 U.S. Dollars) to five million
Kwacha so everyone can make a reasonable living."
</P>
<P>
"We don't want excuses that Zambians cannot make roads
themselves," Chibamba noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed dismay at reports that the bigger road
construction companies operating in Zambia have formed a cartel
where all the smaller ones are being blocked out of business as
they do not have enough finance.
</P>
<P>
"We as government have heard that the 'big boys' are stifling
business for the emerging companies, we will deal ruthlessly with
them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week the World Bank released the 70 million Dollars for
the project to be kicked off next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
