<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, PNA Negotiating Secret Package Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) are quietly negotiating a halt to Israeli
settlement activities in exchange for the delay in Israel's
troop redeployments in the West Bank, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli negotiator, who is attending the current
Israeli-Palestinian talks, was quoted in today's English daily
The Jerusalem Post as saying that the focus of these efforts
are in Washington, where the two sides are trying to work
out a package deal with the help from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The negotiator said the proposed accord would link all Israeli
and Palestinian concerns raised over the past year. The key to the
deal is said to be a trade-off between a Palestinian demand for a
halt in settlements with an Israeli demand that the further
Israeli redeployments in the West Bank be delayed.
</P>
<P>
Israel should have completed the first two stages of the
three-phase redeployments in the West Bank by early September
this year, but the scheduled pullouts have been already
delayed because of the dispute over the scope of
redeployments.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, we are working on questions of how long there
should be such a halt in settlement and whether we can trade that
with a delay or cancellation of the redeployment," said the
Israeli official.
</P>
<P>
The report said that current peace talks, resumed last week
following a seven-month freeze, would not be concluded until an
agreement is reached in Washington. The peace talks will be
shifted to Washington from October 27-31.
</P>
<P>
The PNA Cabinet, which met in Ramallah Saturday, said the
renewed peace talks were in fact stuck and expressed the hope that
U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross, who is to return here today, would
press Israel to implement the interim agreements.
</P>
<P>
"The resumption of committees has not shown any Israeli
willingness to change its position in the interim stage, "said
the Cabinet statement. "It is clear that the Israeli side
does not want the American participation in the works of the
committees."
</P>
<P>
Senior PNA negotiator Saeb Erekat said the forthcoming
Washington agenda will be composed of several points, including a
Palestinian demand for Israel not to take unilateral steps that
will affect the final status of the territories, implementation of
Israeli troop redeployments in the West Bank, security cooperation
against terrorism and completing the work of the nine committees
currently discussing issues that concern previous agreements.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told
Israel Radio's Hebrew service Saturday that he expected the
current progress in the peace process to continue. He also vowed
"there would be no let-up in a war to the death on terrorists"
who seek Israel's annihilation.
</P>
<P>
"In the last weeks there has been progress," Netanyahu said,
adding "We hope this progress will continue and not be halted."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
