<HEADLINE> Falcons Released To Wild In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-three falcons that were
discovered by the Beijing Customs when foreign buyers tried to
smuggle them out of China, have been released to the wild in
northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
And the wild life protection department of Ningxia, entrusted
by the Ministry of Forestry, freed them to Helanshan State Natural
Reserve after they were fed and cared in the Beijing Rare Animals'
Saving Center for a short period.
</P>
<P>
Falcons are a class-2 bird under state protection and Ningxia
is one of their main habitats in China. But, in recent years,
people have been purchasing them illegally for a high price in
southern Ningxia in the counties of Haiyuan, Xiji and
Tongxin. They then sell them at astronomical prices outside China.
</P>
<P>
The Ningxia forestry department and the public security offices
have made an effort to crack down on the illegal trade in falcons,
and information about wildlife protection has made local people more
aware about the protection of the wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen cases of poaching and trade in falcons have been
uncovered since last year, and 42 people penalized, and 29 foreign
buyers expelled from the country. As a result, 37 falcons were
released to nature, according to Bai Xinlian, an official with the
region's Wildlife Protection Office.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to protect wildlife and to crack down on
illegal poaching," said Liu Rongguang, deputy head of the forestry
department of Ningxia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
