<HEADLINE> Central, Eastern Europe Expects Good Grain Harvests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Five central and eastern
European countries Poland, Bulgaria, Hungary, Slovakia and Romania
are all expecting good grain harvests this year.
</P>
<P>
Poland is expected to harvest 24.5-24.8 million tons of grain
in 1997, up 0.3-1.2 percent over last year, according to the
Polish statistics bureau.
</P>
<P>
The wheat output in Bulgaria, which needs 3.8 million tons of
grain annually, will total 3.9 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian government has allocated a large amount of money
for the purchase of surplus grains for export. Slovakia also hopes
to ship 150,000 tons of surplus wheat to the international market
this year.
</P>
<P>
Despite heavy floods this summer, Romania is predicted to
harvest 7.1 million tons of wheat, half of which would be consumed
domestically, according to the figures from the Romanian
statistics bureau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
