<HEADLINE> Priebke Transfer Imminent, Monks Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The seven-month stay of convicted
Nazi war criminal Erich Priebke at a monastery in Frascati outside
Rome is coming to an end, Father Andrea Stefani confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
Stefani told the press here the monks had been told that the
former SS captain will be transferred to a Rome military hospital
by Monday at the latest.
</P>
<P>
But the exact time has not been disclosed, so as to throw
the media off and make the transfer as easy as possible.
</P>
<P>
Priebke was moved to the monastery on March 21 at the end of a
re-trial for his part in Italy's worst World War II atrocity.
</P>
<P>
His arrival was greeted by strong left-wing protests and a
complaint from the town council that he was a painful reminder of
the sufferings of the Roman hill town during the war, when it was
a German army command post.
</P>
<P>
"He's an 84-year-old who does not have long left to live and
who thinks he has entered a tunnel which never seems to an end,"
Stefani said.
</P>
<P>
Priebke was ordered transferred from the monastery to Rome's
Celio military hospital shortly after his re-trial but his lawyers
managed to have the decision frozen.
</P>
<P>
At the re-trial, Priebke was found guilty and sentenced to 15
years in prison for his part in the 1944 Ardeatine Caves massacre
outside Rome. The sentence was later commuted to five years because of
mitigating circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Priebke was one of those who rounded up 335 men and boys and
had them shot in reprisal for a partisan bomb that killed 33
German soldiers in downtown Rome.
</P>
<P>
In his first trial in summer 1996, he was found guilty but
freed because mitigating circumstances were judged to have
triggered the statute of limitations -- a decision that sparked
angry protests which prompted a swift rethink. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
