<HEADLINE> Argentina, U.S. sign Agreement on Global-Warming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Argentina and the United
States signed here Saturday an agreement on global-warming aimed
at cutting emissions of greehouse gases.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Argentine President Carlos
Menem signed the accord during President Clinton's visit to the
country.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, US firms would help Argentina cut carbon
dioxide gases in exchange for credits that would help the United
States to meet its own targets set under a greenhouse gas treaty
to be signed in December in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed the concept on limits on
greenhouse gases, but neither the U.S. nor Argentina said what
those limits are.
</P>
<P>
Europeans are pressing for an emissions cap at 15 percent below
1990 levels by 2010 while the U.S. said such a deep reduction is
unrealistic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
