<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Bank Governor Blasts Credit Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Bank Governor Lutfar
Rahman Sarkar Saturday blamed the banks for siphoning off money
from villages to a few urban rich people, creating social
disparity and willful loan defaulters, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an open discussion on the banking sector, the
central bank chief said the concentration of money in fewer hands,
a result of the disparity between rural and urban areas, is the
single most important problem of the sector.
</P>
<P>
He said the bank collect 22.5 percent of their total deposit,
about 90 billion taka (about 2.05 billion U.S. dollars) of the
total deposit of some 470 billion taka (about 10.7 billion
dollars), from the rural areas while disbursing a very
insignificant amount in the villages.
</P>
<P>
Of the total credit disbursed so far, 60 percent went to the
capital Dhaka region, 20 percent to Chittagong, the second largest
city, and the remaining 20 percent to the entire country, which
reflects the disparity.
</P>
<P>
"Not only that, we also hand over the deposits of the small
savers in the cities, who comprise 70 percent of the total urban
depositors, to the small richer section of the population," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Sarkar said the banks were "patronizing" the richer section,
who make up only five percent of the population but command most
of the default bank loans, now totaling billions of taka.
</P>
<P>
Citing an example, he said only 1,800 people who have 10
million taka (about 0.2 million dollars) or more in default loan,
command a total of 90 billion taka (about 2.05 billion dollars) of
the loans that have already become overdue in different banks and
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, most of them are willful defaulters who can repay,
but don't, said the Bangladesh Bank governor, who blamed the
country's "teethless" laws for such a huge number of loan
defaulters.
</P>
<P>
Sarkar blamed equally the bankers for the default culture,
saying that they only considered the security against the loans
which often misguided them.
</P>
<P>
"But it should be kept in mind that security is not the only
consideration, the man behind the security is the main thing," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that like the economy, the banking sector is
suffering from three diseases - mismanagement, inefficiency and
wasteful expenditure - which, he cautioned, should be addressed
without delay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
