<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chen Yan Depicts Prowess with World Records in Swimming Pool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 19 (Xinhua) -- As a 16-year-old teenager,
woman swimmer Chen Yan became the phenomenon of the National Games
by bettering two world records and two Asian marks for an
unprecented four-time national champion.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy to win four gold medals here, and I've set my
sights upon the World Championshisp in Perth," said Chen Yan, "I
will resume training soon after the Games and will try my best to
achieve good results there."
</P>
<P>
The native swimmer with a height of 1.78 meters first clocked
4:34.79 in the 400-meter individual medley to better the
15-year-old world marks of 4:36.10 set by Petra Schneider, former
East Germany, on August 1, 1982.
</P>
<P>
Then, admist gusts of applauses from the stands, the teenager
of Liaoning province, launched her second attempt towards the
world record in the 200-meter individual medley by finishing in
2:11.27, surpassing the previous mark of 2:11.65 set by Chinese
veteran Lin Li in the Barcelona Games.
</P>
<P>
To further attain her dominance in the pool, the young swimmer
with great potentials, broke two more Asian marks in the 400-meter
and 800-meter freestyles.
</P>
<P>
People wondered about the impetus behind her overnight success
but failed to notice the hardships that she overcame after her
blunder in the Centennial Olympic Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
"I was stunned by the tense atmosphere in Atlanta," recalled
Chen, "and I was plunged into the deep sea after failing to enter
any of the finals in the 200-meter, 400-meter freestyles and the
400-meter individual medley."
</P>
<P>
But coaches and teammates encourged her to overcome the sorrow
and sadness, as many a people, including coach Han Bingyan, sent
the morale-enhancing signal "You are still young, and have great
opportunities ahead. The point is for you to grab the chances
firmly in your own hands."
</P>
<P>
To evaluate her performances in the Olympic Games, it's no
surprise for her defeat as she had been busied in the City's
Games, the Asian Championships and Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
Further more, she suffered ailment to her nose, was refrained
from daily training for two weeks, and failed to regain her top
form while aboarding the plane for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
After the Atlanta Games, Chen busied herself in a four-month
recovery with a daily coverage of 3,000 meters in the pool to
regain her confidence.
</P>
<P>
In January, Chen chopped up six gold medals in the 200-meter
and 400-meter individual medleys in three stops of the World
Short-Course Swimming Championships.
</P>
<P>
In April, Chen anchored her compatriots for her first major
splashes in the world by breaking the short-course world record in
the 4x200-meter relay in Gothenburg.
</P>
<P>
To prepare for the Eighth National Games, Chen, together with
her mentor Han, buried herself in a 27-week intensive training
since May.
</P>
<P>
"The National Games was her first major battle wherein she has
achieved confidence," said Han Bingyan.
</P>
<P>
"And now, I have set my sights upon the World Championships in
January in Perth and the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney," said Chen.
</P>
</TEXT>
