<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin Americans Lukewarm to U.S. Free Trade Area Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 18 (Xinhua) -- United States President
Bill Clinton seemed to have failed to convince the skeptical
Brazilians and Argentines into embracing his plan of creating a
free trade area in the Americas by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Observers say Brazil and Argentina, two key members of the
Southern Cone Common Market (Mercosur), remained lukewarm to
Clinton's plan, fearing the U.S. blueprint to build a Free Trade
Area of the Americas (FTAA) may overwhelm their own bloc.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, keen to reinforce Washington role in Latin America in
the face of growing presence of the European Union and Asia, today
wound up his visit to the three Latin American countries -- widely
seen as a campaign to preach his free trade plan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Brazil and Argentina reiterated their commitment to
the creation of the FTAA, but said they would prefer membership
negotiations in a step-by-step manner.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso was
notably lukewarm to Clinton's notion that Brazil should play a
leading role in creating the FTAA.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Brazil views Clinton's proposal as a threat to
its burgeoning regional status in Mercosur, the largest South
American common market grouping Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and
Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
In Buenos Aires, President Carlos Menem expressed some
reservations, describing the FTAA as "a complex exercise ...
because of the number of disparities of participating actors."
</P>
<P>
"That is why it is indispensable of participating countries to
be able to define their interests at stake," Menem said.
</P>
<P>
The FTAA, to group Mercosur members and NAFTA members of
Mexico, Canada and the United States, was proposed by Clinton in
the Summit of the Americas Conference held in Miami in December
1994.
</P>
<P>
He has been keen in pushing ahead with the plan as Latin
America is getting increasingly important to his country.
</P>
<P>
Among the three countries he visited this time, Venezuela has
replaced Saudi Arabia as the United States' biggest oil supplier.
Brazil is the biggest market of the American continent whereas
Argentina has been granted by the U.S. the status of non-NATO
military ally.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Brazil and Argentina, as key members of the
Mercosur, not only are important trade partners of the United
States but also acquire a growing negotiating capacity before
other economic blocs.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was eager to get his plan implemented as Latin American
countries are accelerating their approach toward the European
Union and Asia.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has already signed with Mercosur a framework
agreement of regional cooperation and decided to hold in 1999 the
first summit meeting of the EU and Latin American countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
