<HEADLINE> Serb Leader Urges Solution to Media Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serb leader Momcilo
Krajisnik today called for an urgent solution to the interruption
of radio and TV broadcast by NATO-led forces in the Bosnian Serb
capital of Pale, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a message to High Representative Carlos Westendorp and
U.N. envoy Kai Eide, Krajisnik said the representatives of the
Serb Radio Television (SRT) and the international community should
open a dialogue, in order to ensure free access to the media for
all parties in the run-up to legislative elections scheduled for
November 23 in the Republic of Srpska.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik, the Bosnian Serb member of the three-member
presidency, also addressed Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic,
asking her to observe the reconciliation agreement reached in
Belgrade earlier last month.
</P>
<P>
The agreement allowed broadcasting stations in Banja Luka and
Pale, respectively the strongholds of Plavsic, who is back by the
West, and her predecessor Radovan Karadzic, to broadcast by turn.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, the NATO-led Stabilization Force in Bosnia seized
three key transmitters of Karadzic's supporters and banned SRT
Pale from broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
But SRT Pale managed to be back on the air with news and
feature programs on October 16 with a transmitter not in the hands
of the SFOR before it was interrupted again by the SFOR today.
</P>
</TEXT>
