<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever Incidence High in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is facing an unusually
high incidence of dengue fever, according to Communicable Diseases
Control Department sources.
</P>
<P>
The latest survey shows that reported cases of dengue fever in
the country rose from 37,929 cases in 1996 to 48,174 in the first
nine months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has also recorded more cases than its neighboring
countries because of the presence of all four strains of the
virus, while other countries, such as Malaysia and Indonesia, have
reported only three strains.
</P>
<P>
Dengue fever, an acute infectious viral disease characterized
by headache, severe joint pain and rash, can lead to shock and
even death, if correct diagnosis is delayed.
</P>
<P>
The disease is spread by certain kinds of house mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Sujitra Nimmanmit, a paediatrist and technical consultant
to the department, attributed the high incidence to inadequate
programs in mosquito controls, limited professionals and slow
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was worst hit in 1987 when about 174,000 people
contracted the illness, leading to about 1,000 deaths.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Sujitra said over the last two decades, dengue fever death
rate in the country has been reduced from 12.5 percent to 0.2
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
