<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Place Where Ancient East and West Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Ancient Europeans and Asians
might have been trading as early as the first century A.D. on the
"Musk Road", Chinese archaeologists said.
</P>
<P>
Based on a series of finds in Tibet's Ngari Prefecture, Zhang
Jianlin, director of the Shaanxi Institute of Archaeology, said
recently that the "Musk Road", which was named after one of its most
popular products, linking ancient Rome and southwest China's
Changdu with the Ngari Prefecture as an important part, was
another cultural link between West and East, in addition to the
much more publicized "Silk Road".
</P>
<P>
Zhang's studies showed that the Golden Age of the "Musk Road"
in the Ngari region was during the Guge Kingdom from the mid-10th
century to the early 17th century.
</P>
<P>
The Guge Kingdom at that time covered a vast area that included
present day Lhasa, Xinjiang, parts of Central Asia, India, and
Nepal and had a population of nearly one million.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that they have found stone implements in Ngari
typical of East Asia, South Asia, North Africa, and Europe.
</P>
<P>
And the Guge Kingdom used the route to export its special local
products, and imported daily necessities from neighboring
countries, the scholar said.
</P>
<P>
Historical documents record a Portuguese missionary describing
trade in the Guge Kingdom, with more than 200 traders from China
coming every year, bringing silk, tea, pottery, and porcelain.
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned businessmen from Central Asia and West Asia
trading cloth, coral, and amber for sheep's wool produced by the
Guge Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Archaeological finds also indicate religious exchanges between
East and West along the "Musk Road".
</P>
<P>
In Ngari, experts can still identify the site of a church built
by Western missionaries at the end of the Guge Kingdom.
Archaeologists have also found fragments of a Bible in Portuguese
in some caves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Echoes From Mercosur (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights
from the Southern Common Market (Mercosur):
</P>
<P>
Mercosur Called "An Irrevocable Reality"
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan Foreign Minister Alvaro Ramos said in
Japan that the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) is "an
irrevocable reality," according to news dispatches received here.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said during the 2nd Mercosur-Japan Meeting at
government-to-government level held in Tokyo October 13 and 14,
that the block will continue advancing toward the creation of "a
common economic space, institutionally consolidated, more
competitive, and more efficient."
</P>
<P>
Brazil Maintains Exemption of Restrictions to its Partners
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The Brazilian government decided October 15
to extend until February 28 of next year the term in which they
will not be restricted in their sales to Brazil, which since April
of this year it imposed to its trade partners as a measure to
reduce its big trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
This measure was announced in a communique form the Central
Bank of Brazil, of which its president Gustavo Franco, admitted
that it was a "political" decision to maintain the cohesion of the
bloc.
</P>
<P>
It is the second postponement of the exemption, because the
Brazilian government did the same thing when this benefit expired
in July of this year.
</P>
<P>
Creation of Mercosur Army Dismissed
</P>
<P>
ROSARIO DO SUL (Brazil) -- Presidents Fernando Henrique Cardoso
of Brazil, and Julio Maria Sanguinetti of Uruguay said here that a
Mercosur army will not be created, but that the cooperation among
its members will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Both presidents made this statement October 16 after they
witnessed, together with Argentine Vice-president Carlos Ruckauf,
the closing of the joint Brazil, Uruguay, and Argentina military
exercise.
</P>
<P>
They also ratified that the armed forces of every one of these
countries will not participate directly in the war against drug
traffic, but will continue supporting police in that field.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Steel Output Increases
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazilian steel output totaled 17.495
million tons from January to August of this year, 6.4 percent more
than the 16.438 million tons of the same period of 1996, announced
the Brazilian Siderurgical Institute.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, main steel producer in the region, expects to produce
this year a little over 26 million tons, 82 percent of the total
Mercosur output, estimated at 32 million tons for this year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil to Attract $24 Billion in Investments Until 1998
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil may receive 24 billion dollars in long term
foreign investments until 1998, which will make of this country
the second pole of attraction for foreign investments among the
emerging economies, second only to China.
</P>
<P>
Brazil received in 1996 direct foreign investments for 9.9
billion dollars, while just in the first eight months of this year
it attracted other 12 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It was officially announced in Brazil that these investments
went to the privatization of the electricity and
telecommunications sectors, among others.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur Economy Ministers's Meeting Postponed
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The meeting of economy ministers and presidents
of central banks of the Mercosur countries was postponed until the
end of this month or the first days of November.
</P>
<P>
The meeting had been foreseen for October 23, and its
postponement was due to the ministers' agenda problems.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the contacts between the member countries
to determine the concrete date for the rendezvous and the themes
to discuss on the occasion continue.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur to Negotiate as Regional Free Trade Bloc
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Mercosur countries will negotiate as a bloc
the creation of the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA), said
Argentine Industry and Commerce Minister Alietto Guadagni.
</P>
<P>
Guadagni said about the recent statements of President Bill
Clinton that the United States and Brazil will lead the destinies
of the region in the 21st century, that "those political
declarations do not involve the commercial aspect, because in the
negotiation process there will be only one voice, that of
Mercosur."
</P>
<P>
Unique Mercosur Telephone Tariff Implemented
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Mercosur Telecommunications Group established
a principle of agreement through which the four member countries
will have a single telephone tariff.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Lombardo, president of the National Telecommunications
Administration (Antel), made the announcement October 17 before
the Uruguayan press.
</P>
<P>
"The Mercosur member countries decided that they must accept
the Antel tariff, because they consider that it is the lowest in
the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
IADB: Mercosur Most Dynamic Integration Processes
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Mercosur is one of the most dynamic multinational
integration processes, among other reasons because it emerged in a
context characterized by the liberalization of the main Latin
American economies.
</P>
<P>
information received here stated that the Interamerican
Development Bank (IADB) praised Mercosur in this way in a report
presented in Washington October 17.
</P>
<P>
The IADB highlights also among other successes, that the
Mercosur partners base their mechanisms of functioning on the
promotion of commerce and investment, but respecting the limits
dictated by the conditions and the dominant micro economic
policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
