<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Echoes From Mercosur (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Clinton Praises Mercosur
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- United States President Bill Clinton praised during
his recent tour of three South American countries the Mercosur
advance, calling it good for the world.
</P>
<P>
He told 1,200 businessmen in Sao Paulo that Mercosur is a good
group, not only for Brazil, but also for his country, because this
agreement increased the commerce among the members of the group
and of Mercosur with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told in Argentina President Carlos Menem that
Mercosur and the Free Trade Agreement of the Americas (FTAA) "do
not antagonize".
</P>
<P>
Brazil, Argentina Sign Agreements With U.S.
</P>
<P>
BRAZILIA -- The governments of Brazil and Argentina signed,
separately, agreements of bilateral cooperation with the United
States during the visit of U.S. President Bill Clinton to both
countries.
</P>
<P>
Brazil and the United States signed October 14 seven agreements
on education, public administration modernization, judicial
cooperation, peaceful use of nuclear energy, technological
cooperation, environmental cooperation, and space cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Two days later, Argentina signed five agreements with the
United States on matters of cooperation in nuclear energy,
environment, and space projects.
</P>
<P>
Another Mercosur Bridge to be Opened in December
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Mercosur will have before the end of this year
a new international bridge over the Uruguay River that will unite
the cities of Santo Tome, in Argentina, and Sao Borja, in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, 1,400 meters long, will cost 40 million dollars, of
which the Argentine and the Brazilian governments will contribute
eight million dollars each, and the rest will come from private
investment.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay Increases Exports to Chile
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Paraguayan exports to Chile increased 4,700
percent in the first eight months of 1997, compared to the same
period of 1996, states a report from Asuncion, Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
Paraguayan Industry and Commerce Ministry figures show that
thanks to the exports of Paraguayan beef, Chilean imports went
from 612,000 dollars to 29.5 million dollars in that period.
</P>
<P>
Notwithstanding, the export of Paraguayan meat to its Mercosur
partners -- Argentina, Brazil, and Uruguay -- dropped 13.2 percent
and its global commerce volume fell 11 percent during the period.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay, Argentina Coordinate Controls in Colonia
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan and Argentine Interior Ministries
agreed October 16 on the installation of a joint control unit of
persons and assets in Colonia, an Uruguayan city that borders with
Argentina across the River Plate.
</P>
<P>
An information exchange mechanism will also be established
between the two national police organizations to speed up the
exchange of information about international criminals, drug
traffic, terrorism, smuggling, and car theft.
</P>
<P>
Both ministries also evaluated and decided to coordinate common
actions in other border ports between both countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
