<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Labor Situation to Get Worse Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 19 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's labor situation will
worsen next year if the exchange rate stays at 35 baht per dollar,
with the services sector growing at only one percent, according to
Thailand Development Research Institute Vice President Nipon
Poapongsakorn.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar Saturday on the labor outlook under
economic uncertainties, he predicted that the Thai labor market
will see more layoffs in 1998 than this year if the country cannot
restore foreign confidence in the Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
If the baht weakens further to 40 baht per dollar, the service
sector, the major employer, will record a negative growth
resulting in unemployment of three to four percent of the total
workforce of 30 million. Peak unemployment used to be only two
percent, he was quoted by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thailand Development Research Institute predicts that
unemployment for this year and next will be 200,000-800,000, while
the Thai Chamber of Commerce says it will rise to 1.3 million next
year.
</P>
<P>
Nipon also urged the Thai government to upgrade educational
standards, especially in the industrial sector. He said more than
74 percent of Thai labor force in the manufacturing sector was not
properly educated and was unskilled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
