<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Hydraulic Project Funded by Whole Nation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 19 (Xinhua) -- The Three Gorges project,
China's largest hydro-electric project, has the support of the
whole nation, the project sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Funds have come in from all over the country for the project,
which began in 1993, and the people of the whole country will
continue to support the project through 2009, when the project is
scheduled for completion, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Funds for the project, which is expected to cost 20 billion
yuan, come mainly from appropriate increases of power rate in
different parts of the country. From 1993 to 1997, some 13.7
billion yuan of such funds has gone into the project.
</P>
<P>
Because of these, the project has been on schedule, and its
first phase goal -- the damming of the Yangtze river -- will be
reached next month.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the country has provided close to three
billion yuan for relocation of residents around the three gorges
area, and help begin more than 1,000 industrial projects to aid
the relocation and poverty alleviation work in the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
