<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hughes Chief Expected to Go to AT&AMP;T </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELOS, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The chief executive of
Hughes Electronics Corp. is expected to depart to head AT&AMP;T, said
a local newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T Corp. may announce Monday that Michael Armstrong will
become its chief executive, Los Angelos Times quoted sources close
to the two companies as saying.
</P>
<P>
After lengthy delays in making its decision, AT&AMP;T offered --
and Armstrong signed -- an employment contract to join New
York-based AT&AMP;T, sources close to the firms said.
</P>
<P>
No details of the agreement were disclosed, and AT&AMP;T and Hughes
spokesmen declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe Armstrong, who is widely credited with
shifting Hughes from a military to a commercial footing, will face
another difficult task at AT&AMP;T: restoring the industry leadership
that the long-distance giant has allowed to slow away.
</P>
<P>
Although total revenue earned by long-distance carriers has
risen consistently since 1984, AT&AMP;T's revenue share has dropped 39
percent over the last 13 years and its share of U.S. long-distance
revenue fell to 51 percent in the second quarter this year,
according to a new report complied by the Federal Communications
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Of course, AT&AMP;T still has a formidable franchise. It has 90
million customers, the industry's best-known brand name and a
global communications network that handles more than 250 million
calls and data transactions a day. Armstrong, who turns 59 today,
will have to find ways to staunch the loss of AT&AMP;T's market share
and to more effectively compete in new growth markets.
</P>
<P>
He is widely considered to be an engaging and politically savvy
executive who is expert at selling his point of view. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
