<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYSE Adopts Measures to Safeguard Securities Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The New York Stock Exchange
(NYSE) has over the past 10 years taken a series of measures to
enhance protection of investors and avoid market crashes.
</P>
<P>
These measures include technological improvements, greater
intermarket cooperation, higher capital and margin requirements
and mechanisms to enhance stability in periods of volatility,
Richard Grasso, chairman and chief executive officer of the NYSE,
said at a press conference here to observe the 10th anniversary of
the stock market crash in 1987.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE's 1.25 billion U.S. dollar investment in technology
since 1987 has vastly increased the ability of the exchange to
handle greater trading volume. The capacity of the system, which
can now handle 2.3 billion shares per day, is about five times
today's average daily volume. Further enhancement will help build
its trading capacity to 3 billion shares per day.
</P>
<P>
This expansion provides a margin of safety well in excess of
what happened in 1987 when the capacity amounted to more than 400
million shares per day, more than twice the average daily volume
of the period. The level was exceeded in October 19 and 20 of
1987, when volume topped 600 million shares each day.
</P>
<P>
Coordination with other exchanges has been enhanced not only
through the functioning of circuit breakers, but through better
communication. A system called "hoot and holler" links the
leadership of al of the exchanges, providing a vital means to
share information and respond efficiently to any crisis situation.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, the NYSE has also established several mechanisms to
ensure orderly trading during periods of market volatility. For
example, the NYSE chairman said, there would be a trading halt for
30 minutes if the Dow Jones Index Average (DJIA) fell 350 points
from the previous day's close, and for 60 minutes if the DJIA fell
550 points.
</P>
<P>
Great improvements have taken place in the efficiency and speed
with which orders are processed, making it far less likely that
any backlogs will occur. In 1987, less than 25 percent of all
NYSE-listed stocks were traded on electronic order books; today
all are. Trades are being displayed more quickly and executed more
rapidly and accurately than at any time before.
</P>
<P>
Now everyone remembers, said the NYSE chairman, that the market
dropped 22.6 percent on October 19, but few recall that the DJIA
was actually up 2 percent in 1987. Since the low of 1666.21 on
October 20, 1987, the value of the Dow has risen close to five
times. A long-term investment perspective has become much more
widespread as a result.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the individual investor, who is the mainstay of
the market, will derive considerable comfort from the steps we
have taken to enhance market stability," Grasso said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Chairman Dies at 65 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Coca-Cola Co. chief Roberto C.
Goizueta, a Cuban immigrant who went on to lead America's most
successful business, died today of lung cancer at the age of 65.
</P>
<P>
Coke's chairman and chief executive officer since 1981,
Goizueta was diagnosed with cancer in September. The heavy smoker
resumed working as he underwent treatment, but last week returned
to a local hospital in Atlanta. A throat infection left him
critically ill because of his chemotherapy-weakened immune system.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola's board met Thursday and decided not to make any
immediate leadership changes. Goizueta had groomed M. Douglas
Ivester, the company president since 1994, to take over, and
analysts expect an uneventful transition.
</P>
<P>
Bold and aggressive, Goizueta ensured Coke's position as the
world's most-recognizable brand product while making the
Atlanta-based company one of Wall Street's most valuable. Coke's
value zoomed dramatically from 4 billion U.S. dollars in 1981 to
nearly 150 billion U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Diet Coke and caffeine-free drinks joined Coca-Cola products in
the '80s and did well, but Goizueta's decision to come out in 1985
with New Coke was a classic blunder. The company brought back the
old formula, dubbed "Classic," after three months.
</P>
<P>
Goizueta moved Coke into new markets in China, India and Russia
and many other countries.
</P>
<P>
The experience helped drive Goizueta's leadership.
</P>
<P>
He earned a chemical engineering degree at Yale University,
then returned home to the family business in 1953. He answered an
ad for a bilingual chemical engineer or chemist, and found himself
going to work for Coca-Cola on July 4, 1954 in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
He arrived in the U.S. in 1960 and moved in 1964 to company
headquarters and was elected vice chairman in 1979, president the
following year and chairman and CEO on March 1, 1981.
</P>
<P>
He also paid close attention to giving investors a better
return. A 100-U.S. dollar investment in Coca-Cola when Goizueta
took the top job would be worth about 6,500 U.S. dollars today,
including reinvested dividends.
</P>
<P>
Today, the company stands as the fourth most valued company in
the United States, and Goizueta was the 120th richest man in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Goizueta is survived by his wife, Olga, their three children,
and eight grandchildren. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971019.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Achieves New Economic Growth: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's structural adjustment
program has achieved progress at the financial and economic
levels, an annual report issued by the Central Bank of Egypt (CBE)
has said.
</P>
<P>
The report on Egypt's monetary and credit developments said
that the gross domestic product (GDP) grew by 5.3 percent in the
fiscal year of 1996/97, which went from July 1, 1996 to June 30,
1997, compared with the growth rate of 5 percent in the previous
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was submitted today to the People's Assembly
of Egypt, attributed the growth to the development in the sectors
of agriculture, industry, transport, tourism, construction and
housing.
</P>
<P>
Investment rose to 21 percent of the GDP in the 1996/97 fiscal
year, against 19.7 percent in 1995/96, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Budget deficit in 1996/97 was kept as low as 1 percent of the
GDP, resulting from rationalization of public expenditures and
development of public revenues.
</P>
<P>
The CBE report indicated that the annual inflation rate in the
1996/97 fiscal year declined to 6.2 percent, compared to 7.3
percent in the previous fiscal year, while the value of banking
deposits rose by 14.7 percent to reach 2,000.6 billion Egyptian
pounds (about 588.41 billion U.S. dollars) till last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
